  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions is complex and evolved over time. Here's a brief overview:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Historically, efforts to track financial transactions emerged to combat tax evasion and organized crime\n- Initial anti-money laundering (AML) laws focused on disrupting criminal financial networks\n\n2. United States Developments:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970) - First major legislation requiring financial institutions to report large cash transactions\n- Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations Act (RICO) (1970) - Expanded legal tools to combat organized crime financial activities\n- Money Laundering Control Act (1986) - Explicitly criminalized money laundering as a federal crime\n\n3. International Developments:\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989\n- Established international standards for combating money laundering\n- Developed recommendations for national legal and regulatory AML frameworks\n\n4. Post-9/11 Expansion:\n- Patriot Act (2001) significantly expanded AML and counter-terrorism financing regulations\n- Increased reporting requirements and enhanced investigative capabilities\n- Broadened definitions of financial crimes\n\n5. Ongoing Evolution:\n- Continuous updates to address emerging technologies and financial practices\n- Increased focus on cryptocurrency and digital financial transactions\n\nThe legal framework continues to develop in response to changing financial technologies and criminal methodologies.",
